  "doc_id": "8785",
  "text": "In Type 1 Diabetes (T1D), the use of recombinant insulin to maintain normoglycemia does not address the underlying cause of the disease, T cell mediated β cell destruction. T1D dendritic cell (DC) therapy addresses this issue by promoting β cell specific self-tolerance via modification of the T cell response. The use of DC to circumvent T1D progression and promote β cell self-tolerance was first investigated approximately 2 decades ago. DC from the pancreatic draining lymph nodes of non-obese diabetic (NOD) mice prevented the onset of T1D when adoptively transferred to NOD mice at an early stage of the disease [CITATION_1] . Since that time numerous studies have investigated the effectiveness of bone marrow derived dendritic cells (BM-DC) in preventing T1D in NOD mice [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [4] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . These studies have",
